segments.text: Was he a former Yale leader?
No, he was not.
Okay.
He was in the Corps and then he went on to get his graduate degree and then went to Tech for a while and then came back.
And when you went out of town, normally what did you all wear?
We had travel uniforms.
we would wear, it was always up to the yell leaders to picket and that the university would provide those as well.
Like we had khaki pants, a shirt that had embroidered yell leader in our class year, the block A&M, and then jackets for when it was cold.
Alright, Landon Shreveport, how long was it before somebody recognized you as an Aggie yell leader?
Right off the plane.
Simply because there were five guys, all with the same haircut, all wearing the same thing.
And so either an IU would recognize us or someone would ask us.
I mean, it was all the time.
And they were cordial?
Very cordial, very cordial.
Even people from other schools, that was the neat thing, except Texas Tech.
Texas Tech and University of Texas were the two that just were bad.
Okay, then, so Louisiana Tech.
Then where was the next big out-of-town game?
Probably Missouri was really big.
I think that was the last one of the year.
I remember Nebraska was a big out-of-town game.
Up there?
Yeah.
We went to Nebraska, to Oklahoma City, to Missouri, to Shreveport.
and then to Tech that year.
I think those were our five away games.
What was your impression of a game at Lincoln?
Amazing.
Lincoln, Nebraska is amazing for football.
The fans, very similar fans as far as A&M and Nebraska goes.
Undying support for their team and they aren't rude to the opposing team.
It was great.
Usually when we went places we'd get some funny looks.
People would make fun of us simply because of what we were wearing, what we were doing.
Never happened in Nebraska.
They gave a standing ovation to our band.
They, when we were doing it after the game, we have a yell practice when we obviously get outscored when the time runs out.
And so we did our yell practice.
Then afterwards, people were just coming up, left and right, just being like, man, we're so impressed with y'all.

The fact that y'all are yelling even though you were down, it was just, it was very, it was a good feeling, you know, just because you got support even though we didn't necessarily deserve it, you know, which was really neat.
I was a chancellor at Missouri, but before, what was your impression there?
Missouri was neat, and it was neat simply because we had lost a couple games, and then we won that one, and so it was really good.
It was like a running upswing.
I remember being very happy about us winning.
We stayed in St. Louis, and it was a really good time simply because I'd been saving money, and I got to take Kate with me up to Missouri.
Now, she went to Shreveport with us, and
She went to Oklahoma City, but she went to Oklahoma City because she drove.
But I bought Kate a plane ticket to go to St. Louis with us.
So that was a really, really neat weekend for us.

and right then like dusty who was one of the senior leaders he hadn't had a girlfriend and he had just gotten a girlfriend a couple months before so he brought her as well and so we just had a really good time that was a really fun time for the five of us to have fun in another city because we had time to do so does that make sense so we really just kind of walked around st louis kind of experienced what st louis was because i had never been there before so that was
The thing that I'm going to pull away from Yell Leader so much is just the opportunities that it gave me that I just wouldn't have had otherwise.
I mean, I just wouldn't have had it.
For instance, something that we got to do, the volleyball team did really good last year when I was a junior Yell Leader.
They made it to the Sweet 16 of the NCAA tournament, and our bracket was in Honolulu, Hawaii.
So we got to go to Hawaii.
So there's five of us.
I picture there's five Yell Leaders there.

three twenty two year olds one twenty one year old and one twenty year old and we go to hawaii we have rusty doesn't go with us so it's pretty much the five of us with no chaperones for five days the week of finals okay so we missed all our finals and we get out of them someone had to take a final there but the rest of us we just thankfully our teachers helped with it worked with us and we took them before or afterwards so we go to hawaii and none of us had ever been to hawaii before
And it was just absolutely hysterical.
It was the five of us with the volleyball team and the volleyball team coaches and some people in the athletic department.
And we just had the time of our lives.
I mean, first thing we did, we got off the plane, we went and rented scooters.
And the guy who rented his scooters was just this, I mean, it was just funny.
Like we still sit around and every once in a while when we get back together, the old guys from last year will tell stories about that trip.
I mean, those are going to be stories that we talk about.
for a long time.
During that first fall as a Yale leader, how much time did you spend of your waking moments?
Doing something having to do with Yale leader?
Yeah.
60%, 70% of my waking time.
What about your class attendance rate?
It was relatively good.
You find that Yale leaders, unless they're just people that don't care about grades, but if they have any care about grades, their grades get better once they become a Yale leader.

They take less hours, obviously, but their grades become better because most people, when you get busy, you budget your time better, you study better, you don't waste as much time, which leads to a very active lifestyle and you don't get to rest a lot, but...
It was good.
Like, it was really good.
I remember... Well, there were some classes that I just didn't go to because I didn't like them.
But...
Missed a lot of Friday classes, obviously, for away games.
There was one teacher who just didn't... Just could care less what I was.
And they just didn't budge an inch.
Didn't budge an inch about stuff.
I remember it was an English class.
It was English 222 World Literature with Snodgrass.
Mr. Snodgrass.
Dr. Snodgrass.
I don't know.
Anyway.
And...
I had done something out at the bonfire site.
It's just a tradition that the Y'all Leaders did out there, and I was there until 5.15 in the morning.
So I went home, and I was relatively physically bruised, and my hands were bloody and stuff like that, simply because of the work that I was doing.
And I remember I had to clean up, put bandages on, all that kind of stuff, and then by the time that came around, it was about 7.30.
So what I did is I just went, ate breakfast, got some coffee, and...
I didn't make it to class perfectly on time.
It was an 8 o'clock class.
I got there like at 8.05.
And we have quizzes, random attendance quizzes.
And I didn't make it to that quiz.
And so right after the class period, I walked downstairs and I walked down and talked to him.
I was like, sir, is there any way that maybe I could make up this quiz?
I was doing something, something, something along those lines.
And he said, well, you should have thought about that when you run, shouldn't you?
Now, and so your first year as a yield leader is 99.
And did you, as a yield leader, did you go out to the cut area?
I never went out to cut, no.
We were always doing stuff on weekends, obviously game weekends or whatever.
It was never one of those things where we had the time to go put in to cut.
But went out to the stack site a couple times.
And where were you when you heard?
I was in my room.
How did you hear?
Someone knocked on the door.
You were asleep?
Yeah, I was asleep.
This is off campus?
No, I was on campus.
I lived in Aston Hall.
I moved back on campus my junior year.
I moved back onto campus.
Once I made Yell Leader, I realized that there's just no way I could maintain that schedule without being on campus.
So I moved onto Southside, Aston Hall.
And I remember, it was funny, I had a Yell Leader function that night.
And I remember walking in.
I was good friends with the crew chiefs in my dorm.
So I remember walking into my dorm and them getting ready to go do their shift.
Aston Hall was one of the ships that were out there that night.
And Bill Davis, who is actually a friend of mine who is our crew chief, he is actually one of the ones injured.
He broke his arm real bad.
But I remember them being there and them yelling, hey, Ricky, do you want to go out there tonight?
And I remember this is so plain to me.
Like, here's the corner of the wall.
They're standing down there.
My room is down there.
And I remember standing there.
And I thought about it for like a minute, like for a good 15, 20 seconds.
I was like, can I go?
I was like, when's the next shift?
And they're like, we're doing it tomorrow night.
And I was like, man, I got a quiz tomorrow morning.
I was like, I'll come tomorrow night.
So they're like, OK, fine.
So I went to my room.
Did whatever my room went to sleep about.
2.40 in the morning, someone knocked on the door and said, hey, bonfire just fell.
We need to see who's in the dorm and who's not.
So I run back out.
I mean, of course, I run out to the field, and I'm just out on the field the rest of the morning.
How long before you knew that someone of your acquaintance was hurt?
Was hurt.
A couple hours.
I mean, I knew quite a few of the people they got.
I knew two of the guys that actually passed away.
When you got to the site, how many people were there observing?
A couple hundred.
There were a couple hundred.
Was there any emergency equipment already there?
Yes.
Yes, there was emergency equipment there.
As far as you can now determine, looking back,
Was there any reaction to Bonfire in terms of what people tried to do soon after the collapse?
Define the question, what do you mean?
Like physically try to do, like help?
Yeah, it's fallen.
Is there anything that people did after that that was an error or that they failed to do that they should have done?
Like, I have the impression just about everybody reacted about as well as they could have.
Yeah, I don't think anything could have been done differently.
I mean, you can't just go in there and start pulling logs, obviously.
But, yeah, I mean, from my take on the situation, everything was handled great.
Did all the other Yale leaders, were they all out there?
Not with, at different times we went out there.
I remember seeing a couple of them sometimes.
But you went as an individual?
I went as an individual.
Not as a young man?
No, I went as myself.
I went as Ricky.
And how long did you stay out there?
I was out there until about 10, 15.
In the morning?
In the morning.
And what were you and your buddies, your closest friends, what were you all thinking, saying, doing?
Well, actually we had a meeting
about what we were going to do, just because obviously Bonfire was in four days.
And as a Yale leader, Bonfire was a big part of what we did, so we had to decide what we were going to do, what was going to happen.
Had a couple meetings with the Vice President of Student Affairs, had a couple meetings just the five of us, came up with ideas, came up with what we wanted to do.
I remember just standing out there, I remember this really vividly, just standing out there
And just sitting, and honestly just sitting.
And my phone, I had my cell phone on me at that time, and my cell phone was just running off the hook.
I mean, every three seconds, I'd be on the phone and another call would come in.
I mean, it was everybody from my parents to friends that I hadn't seen since first grade, my principals.
I mean, everybody, anyone that knew that I was a Yale leader, just because they knew that Yale leaders had a lot to do with bonfire.
So they didn't know if I was on the stack or not.
Did you see, did you visibly see some of the victims who were picked up and taken?
I did.
Our number three son is a radiologist at St. Joseph, and he was on call that night.
He does not talk about it at all.
Because I get the impression, this is my conclusion, so that he's innocent of it, but I get the impression that some of the x-rays that he looked at and saw, just people just squashed and impressed.
Then I have in there on my desk Mrs. Curley's
just finished book about what she and her husband went through.
The son, he died one day before his father's birthday.
Guess what his SAT score was?
Tested out a 45.
He was an amazing kid.
Did everybody pool together?
Yes.
Totally.
It was amazing.
I remember going to the service we had that night in Reed Arena.
And I went, and I remember getting there about an hour and a half early and getting one of the seats near the front on the floor.
And just, I mean, it was amazing.
Like, you couldn't describe it.
You just couldn't describe it.
Now you said that you Yale leaders discussed what you all thought were going to recommend.
What did you all recommend?
To have a Yale practice.
To have a modified Yale practice.
To have something...
It couldn't be... Because the thing that we didn't want is there was all this talk about...

doing away with the rivalry you know this rivalry you know 12 students have died and yes 12 students have died i'm not taking away from that at all but what we did not want to do was have another memorial service we didn't want to have another memorial service there was going to be that the candlelight vigil that night we didn't want to have another
memorial service in Caulfield is essentially what it was.
And there was a football game the next day, and it was a big football game.
The University of Texas was number five in the nation at that point.
That was a very big time for us.
And we didn't want it to be another memorial service.
And so we tried to come up with stuff to which would be uplifting.
And that night, there's probably six memories that are going to stay with me for the rest of my life.
Oh, cool.
Just visually.
Describe those.
From Yell Leader.
See if I can remember them.
One is definitely...

That night, that night on the cow field with all, when the cannon is, I don't know if you were there or not, but there was a point in the Yale practice when the cannon 12, fired 12 times and we were arm and arm at the 50 yard line.
And there were all the candles around us.
And literally, I mean, we were five grown men that were just weeping, just weeping.
That was amazing.
That was one.
Another one was when we won the next day when we beat Texas in a game where we shouldn't have won.
But we won.
That was amazing.
As you saw the team in action, were you aware that they seemed to have something?
Very much so.
Being in that locker room, it was really neat being in the locker room before the games just because you got to see the team and you got to see how they warmed up.
And it was completely different.
There was just a different feel.
How?
What was the feel?
Was it quieter?
Yeah.
It wasn't as loud, honestly.
More serious?
Much more serious.
It's like there was a purpose other than just football that day.
And did the coaches seem to reflect that too?
Very much so.
Very much so.
It was... And were you on the field when the Longhorn band?
I was.
I was on the field.

I couldn't see it, honestly, because one of the requirements, not requirements, but one of the things we do is we kind of guard the field during the bands because we don't want anyone running down out of the field.
And so we are on a knee at the 50-yard line on the visitor's side.
And so we really can't see anything.
So we didn't see the front and see what they were doing.
But we heard about it.
And we heard obviously a lot of cheering and a lot of whooping.
So we heard that that was amazing.
And you heard Amazing Grace.
Obviously.
Obviously.
That's one of the things was singing Amazing Grace in Reed Arena that night.
Just how it just spurred up.
And no one wanted to leave.
That was amazing.
It really, truly was.
All right.
Now that, obviously, the toughest, most serious moment of that whole season.
Go to the other extreme now.
What were some of the goofiest moments of being a first year?
Goofiest moments of being a first year?
Yeah.
Do you remember goofing up yourself and getting the wrong yell?
Oh man, I remember one time we were doing fish camps.

one of the requirements during the summer that we do is we go up and we do the yell practices at fish camp and it was the first one and we were so nervous because this was the first time that we were in front of actually new students we had done the new student conferences okay parents were there it wasn't a big deal this is completely students okay right now we are doing our job we are teaching yells and we're doing a full yell practice and oh man i was just so nervous like i was flipping out i get up there and i say okay this is the yell that we're going to do and i pass it back and i teach the wrong yell
I teach the wrong yell.
And I remember doing it and just going... And the head yell at the time, Jeff Bailey comes up and is like, oh, you got him, Ricky.
That was a good joke.
And so then I was like, oh, yeah, it was.
And so then we teach the other one.
And so I taught the other one.
But we got in a lot of trouble that night.
Because I wasn't the only one that messed up.
The other junior messed up as well.
And so we got in trouble that night.
The ride home was not fun, let's put it that way.
Oh, for you sophomores.
I mean, you juniors.
Yeah, the ride home wasn't fun.
Because we messed up.
The seniors didn't mess up.
If the seniors would have messed up, then we would have been okay.
But the seniors didn't mess up, and we did.
And so it was bad.
But it was a learning experience.
It was one of those, I never messed up a yell again.
I was always... Oh, I'm about to sneeze.
Um...
It was always one of those things where whenever you did mess up you always learned from it and you always made sure not to do it again.
Alright, let's see, did you ever though running across the field somewhere fall?
Oh, many times.
Oh man, I can remember one time definitely that

especially during midnight yell practice was the worst just because all the juniors would be down on the field so I remember one time doing a yell or singing the Spirit of Aggieland and then finishing and then whooping and just turning around and running and I mean right when I did it this guy and we just went all over the entire track

other times during the during games obviously you're just sprinting i mean you're running as fast as you can to go down to behind the goal post when we score and i can remember times just taking out a media person i mean just bullying right over them and just being like sorry and running on um
Did any old time former students ever try to give you or your buddies any advice on how to do?
The yell themselves?
How to lead, be a yell leader?
Um, yeah, of course they did.
Everyone always, especially,
It's funny, the old Yale leaders wouldn't say as much as old students.
Oh, okay.
Old students feel like, and this is just A&M, old students that were just here and saw it feel like that they know more about it than, let's say, someone who actually did it.
Not because they think that in their mind, but we got more people giving us advice that were never Yale leaders.
What did they think you ought to do more of or less of?
Well, just depending on the yell.
They said do this yell more, do this yell not more, change this yell, do this differently, why don't you do this anymore, why do you do this now?
People have a hard time with change, especially here.
Are there any yells that they said used to be done that aren't being done anymore?
Yeah, there's a lot.
We actually have a yell book from the 1920s.
Wow.
that one of my friends had that we looked through, and there's just a lot of yells in there that we don't do anymore.
It's funny.
Back to any other funny moments, goofy moments in the first year?
Man, there are so many, and I was trying to think of them today.
I wish I could have gone back through and looked at stuff.
The Hawaii trip was really fun, just because I remember this.
No one really laughed at this except us, but in Hawaii...

We didn't have a lot of money and so we didn't want to go and spend so we did a lot of going and buying stuff at convenience stores and bringing it back to our room and just sitting in on our room and just being loud and crazy there.

We were on like the 12th floor of this hotel room and if this was the street then this right here was where our hotel was and our room was right here and so you're about there on the street mid balconies and we
We would get toilet paper and we'd make spitballs about that big.
And then we'd just get a running start in the room and just chunk them out onto the street.
And you'd hit cars going by.
You'd hit pedestrians down on the street.
We did that for literally about four hours.
Just sat there and just threw spitballs.
They weren't spitballs, but they were water balls, I guess you could call them.
That was a lot of fun.
That was really funny.
There's
And by then, I'm gathering that... Yeah, we were very close.
You're pulling together.
Yeah, we definitely are pulling together.
And were you supportive when anybody had a personal problem?
Did the other Yale leaders...
Very supportive.
Something that I think, in my opinion, was one of the big steps that happened for us was when, after the first game against Tulsa that year, we played Tulsa for first Yale.
Mm-hmm.
I think that's right.
Didn't we play Tulsa?
I don't know if you can remember.
I think we were.
I think we played Tulsa.
Anyway, our first home game that year, the first jail weekend, we won.
Fish came down and tackled us and picked us up.
Well, in between Kyle Field and Fish Pond, they ripped my uniform off me because they were told somehow that that was a good bull because since I was the non-reg.
This is your senior year?
This is my junior year.
Oh, your junior year.
My junior year.
That was something good to do.
It was a good bull to do.
So they ripped my uniform off me.
Well, I get to Fish Pond, and I don't have a shirt on.
I mean, I have my undershirt on, but I don't have my yell leader uniform on.
And my pants are all torn and stuff like that.
And Jeff, people were just like, what happened?
I was like, the fish ripped my uniform off me.
And they just, I mean, they were livid.
Supposedly the next morning in Duncan, or the next Monday morning in Duncan, Jeff Bailey stood up and gave a talk that...
People have said we'll go down as the biggest chewing, ass chewing that they've heard in Duncan Dining Hall since they've been in school.
Just about that they shouldn't do that.
And so that, one, I think it, I didn't make a big stink of it.
I didn't go to the battalion.
I didn't go to my friends on Northside.
I didn't do any of that and said, look at what these CTs are doing.
I just was like, that's an unfortunate situation, you know.
I didn't really know how to handle it.
I remember being really hurt.
I remember leaving that going.
Why am I doing this?
Why am I trying?
Why am I doing all this?
And it turned out fine.
And so that was really good.
I think that was a big step up for us, just as far as trusting the other person.
All right.
Now, by this, your junior year, you're so busy that you don't have many free weekends to travel much.
Did you go out of town much other than Yell Eater?
Not that I can remember.
Where did you and your buddies go just to have a good time on Saturday night?
We went to a couple places actually.
Sophomore year, we went to a place called the Ptarmigan, which was a bar over in Bryan on South College.
We go to P-T-A-R. P-T-A-R, Ptarmigan, I guess you could so call it.
My junior year, we went to a lot of houses, I remember, just because a lot of my friends weren't 21 yet, even though I was 21.
Northgate, I became much more a frequenter of Northgate simply because I turned 21 somewhere before my junior year.
So my friends and I, we'd go to Northgate.
I never really went to the chicken a lot, amazingly enough.
People always talk about the Dixie chicken.
I never really started frequenting the chicken until this year.
Now I go a lot.
But then I never really went.
How common was underage drinking publicly?
Very common.
It's cut down a lot in the past couple years.
It's still done all over the place.
But it's cut down a lot simply because TABC has kicked up a lot more.
How often during those years did people really get drunk?
A lot.
A lot.
And they were drinking beer?
Sometimes.
It depended on where you were.
The chicken, yes.
All you do is drink beer.
You go to places like Dudley's, you drink beer.
You go to places like the Dry Bean Saloon, that's just a shot bar.
So there's really not... And was it whiskey?
Depended.
I mean, it was everything from whiskey to there's a couple shots that have huge stories that go with them.
I mean, there's a lot of stuff.
And how often did you, were you aware there were some people doing drugs?
Actually, drugs were never done on Northgate that I always saw.
When people would do drugs, they'd do them at houses.
They'd do them at parties.
I never saw hardcore drugs.
I would see marijuana a lot.
But I never really saw any hardcore drugs.
Marijuana, you could just smell it.
So you'd know what was going on.
As far as you know, where were people buying the marijuana?
From other students.
Here in town?
Yeah, here in town.
How was it coming to town?
I know a lot of my friends that did it.
They would get it from students that went to Blinn.
But were the Blinn students buying it from somebody?
I have no idea.
I never got that.
I didn't do that, so I never, I just kind of steered clear of all that stuff.
And what would be your guess as to what percentage of students today smoke cigarettes, tobacco?
Smoke cigarettes?
I'd say a whole lot of people do every once in a while.
Not as a habit, but I'd say people do, I'd say 40% of students
Do it every once in a while?
Do Aggie women smoke as much as Aggie, in percentages, as much as Aggie men?
The ones that I hang around do.
Or is it more?
No, it's the same.
It's the same.
But see, I don't hang around anyone that smokes all the time.
Like I don't have any smoker friends.
But yet if we go out, we'll go out to Northgate one night and someone will buy a pack of cigarettes and 20 of us will have a cigarette together, you know.
Are there some places here in the Bryan area that students go to that are clearly dangerous for them?
Martin Luther King and Bryan, Martin Luther King Boulevard and Bryan.
It's really dangerous.
Okay.
I think it's pretty dangerous for women at night anywhere.
Anywhere.
Especially, I mean, it always, I always don't know why, but I always see girls jogging at night on campus.
It just scares the trash out of me.
I just, I don't even know why.
It's dumb.
It is very dumb.
As much as we want to think that this is a really nice place and there's no bad people, I mean, that's just not true.
That's just not true at all.
Now, you've heard the old legends about La Grange.
The best little...
The best little whorehouse?
Oh, sure.
Now, there is nothing like that anywhere.
As far as whorehouses?
Not that I know of.
There's nothing like that anywhere now.
Not that I know of, no.
And I don't think you'd be surprised.
No one I have interviewed knows anybody that actually went to LaGrange.
They heard people did, but they don't know anybody.
Of course not.
Why would you know anybody who went to LaGrange?
All right, did...
How did that affect your participation in religious activities?
brought it down, honestly, just because I didn't have the time to go do it.
Like, I'd be doing, I'd go and speak to organizations on Tuesday nights, so I wouldn't be able to go to Breakaway, per se.
I wouldn't, I wasn't able to, I didn't have the opportunity to participate in a Bible study through Ecumenical Club, the organization I was in.
I was out of town a lot on Sundays.
In terms of values, your code of ethics and so forth,
Did you come to realize that your fellow Yale leaders were similar?
Very similar, which was really neat.
It was actually a big encouragement when I did find that out.
It helped a lot.
I actually live with one of the senior Yale leaders now.
He's my roommate.
And were all of you Anglos?
Yes.
Actually now, oh no, no, actually there was a Catholic.
There was a Catholic.
Okay.
Yeah.
Okay.
The, all right, that junior year as a Yale leader, when the year is over, what had happened to your GPA compared to the previous years?
It had gone down like a point, like point one.
Oh, point one, not a full point.
No, no, no, like a tenth of a point.
Okay.
Still above three?
Yeah, I still, it's still above three right now.
Okay.
I, the first time I had ever gotten below three was last fall.
All right.
Then you ran for senior yell leader in that spring.
Describe that campaign.

That campaign, well, first off, something that really neat happened was the Corps didn't run anyone against me, which to my knowledge is the first time that that's ever happened, that the Corps of Cadets has not put up five people.
Why didn't they?
I don't know.
You know, everybody has kind of their thoughts on it.
If I were trying to toot my own horn, I'd say, well, they liked me so much and they liked the job that I did that they wanted me to be there again.
But I don't think that's necessarily true.
I think it was a combination of them seeing, okay, he did the job, he knows how to do the job the best, and why wouldn't we want to re-elect that?
And also, they didn't think that they could, they wouldn't be able to put someone up that could beat me.
Alright, as far as you know, who is it in the Corps that decides who is going to run for what from the Corps?
Originally, it's called core block.
I mean, I know the answer.
